<TITLE> UK's FSA expects December update from Northern Rock </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Dec 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's financial watchdog told legislators on Tuesday it still expects beleaguered mortgage bank Northern Rock Plc to publish a trading update this month, before the close of its financial year. "It would be a pre-close statement, and then a (full) statement after the end of the year," Hector Sants, chief executive of the Financial Services Authority told the cross-party Treasury Select Committee. Answering repeated questions over whether Northern Rock was expected to publish a trading statement by mid-December, in line with what the bank had previously said, he added it would have to update the market in order to fulfil its listing conditions. Sants, alongside FSA Chairman Callum McCarthy, was giving evidence to parliament's Treasury Committee as part of an inquiry into financial stability. Until its near-collapse in September, Northern Rock was traditionally one of the first banks to update the market. The period for trading updates typically runs to mid-December. Northern Rock, which has said it expects an update in early December, declined to comment further on Tuesday. Northern Rock advisers are auctioning the bank after it was engulfed in a funding crisis in September and has since been forced to borrow 25 billion pounds ($51.2 billion) from the Bank of England. Northern Rock's volatile shares were down 3.3 percent at 105.9p at 1301 GMT. Asked about the volatility in the stock, both FSA heads said they did not see the conditions for the shares to be suspended. The FSA has come under fire over its role in the Northern Rock crisis, putting the watchdog through its toughest test since it was set up seven years ago. McCarthy and Sants confirmed that a key discussion paper on the regulation of liquidity was expected this month, with the results of a "forensic" look at its role in the Northern Rock debacle due by next spri
